          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Howard Lutnick, US Secretary of Commerce, stands at the White House. Credits: REUTERS/ Elizabeth Frantz</p> 
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            The US economy expanded at a 2.3% annualized rate in the fourth quarter of 2024, down from 3.1% in the previous quarter. While consumer spending remained strong at 4.2%, growth was hampered by <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-01-03-2025-h1-1-weaker-investment-and-concerns-over-tariffs?source=website" target="_blank">weaker investment and concerns over tariffs</a>. Inflation was revised to 2.7%, potentially complicating future Fed rate decisions.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Harsh winter weather in January also impacted retail sales, housing, and job growth. Tariffs imposed by the Trump administration have raised fears of higher prices and economic strain. Despite these challenges, the economy grew 2.8% in 2024, above the Federal Reserve’s estimated non-inflationary rate of 1.8%.</p>
        </mj-text>
