            <strong>
            🇿🇦 G20 Finance meeting concludes without consensus</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           The recent G20 Finance Ministers and Central Bank Governors meeting in Cape Town concluded <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-01-03-2025-wn1-3-without-a-joint-communique?source=website" target="_blank">without a joint communique</a>, highlighting divisions among nations. Key absentees, including finance ministers from the US, China, Japan, and India, hindered consensus on critical issues. Discussions centered on climate finance, with South Africa urging developed nations to support poorer countries’ green energy transitions. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Trade protectionism and unilateral policies, particularly from the US, were also contentious topics. Additionally, African leaders advocated for collective debt relief to address the financial burdens of the world’s poorest nations. Despite extensive deliberations, differing viewpoints prevented a unified agreement.</p>
        </mj-text>
