            <strong>🇪🇸 Foreign workers drive Spain’s economic boom</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5; filter: blur(5px);">
            Spain’s economy is outperforming the rest of Europe, growing by 3% in 2024, largely due to an <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-01-03-2025-wn3-5-influx-of-foreign-workers?source=website" target="_blank">influx of foreign workers</a>. Nearly 45% of jobs created since 2022 have been filled by migrants, making up 13% of the workforce. Spain attracts economic migrants from Latin America who integrate quickly due to language similarities. 
            </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5; filter: blur(5px);">Newcomers often take service jobs, such as construction, farming, fishing, and home care. With an aging population, the country needs more workers in the coming decades. Despite rising anti-immigration sentiment in Europe, Spain’s policies promote legal migration to sustain its economy and social security system.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
